<h2>Melodic Patterns</h2>

<p>On the guitar, it requires some fairly odd fretboard patterns that (for me,
at least) are a great knuckle-busting workout. Here, I’ve chosen a pattern that
I find sounds like a nice melody, and is good for working on hammer-ons and
pull-offs. I follow the same pattern of scale degrees:</p>

<p>④: 1 — 2<br/>
③: 3 — 5<br/>
②: 6 — 7<br/>
①: 8 — 9 — 10 — 8<br/>
②: 6 — 7 — 5<br/>
③: 4 — 5 — 3<br/>
④: 1 — 2 — 7 — 1</p>

<p>as I move up through the modes of Melodic Minor. This also takes us up to the
22nd fret, where that legato playing is extra tough. I cannot do this smoothly
yet, at all. For maximum mystique, I do as much of it as I can without picking:
start each string with a <a
href="https://www.premierguitar.com/lessons/hammer-ons-from-nowhere">hammer-on
from nowhere</a>. Good practice!</p>

<iframe src="study.pdf" width="100%" height="500" loading="lazy"></iframe>

<p>Here’s the MIDI robot:</p>

<audio src="study.mp3" controls></audio>

<p>The little numerals to the left of the note heads are fretting-hand
fingerings. 1 = pointer, 2 = middle, 3 = ring, and 4 = pinky. These are just my
suggestions; this is a weird scale, so no fingering is going to be as easy as
the good ol’ pentatonic box. As always, try out various fingerings and use what
works best for you.</p>
